{[%evp 11,83,22,33,20,43,36,43,36,51,55,48,49,24,12,4,-107,-82,-85,156,121,144,121,220,185,247,229,229,195,220,172,268,221,231,237,217,88,157,34,32,33,36,15,23,24,48,27,37,13,88,57,67,97,104,96,172,184,322,254,271,256,280,270,358,334,356,325,476,492,558,490,465,480,712,672] B40: Sicilian: 2...e6, Unusual lines The preparation for a match became more seriously. Chess books had an inferior level and opportunities for practice were sparse at the beginning of the nineteenth century. Openings could be studied by Bilguer's Handbuch des Schachspiels' and games by chess journals half-a-century later. The train enabled training in other cities. Anderssen and Morphy utilised the new chances for the first time.  Their approach to chess is comparable with La Bourdonnais. Pieces are developed as fast as possible in order to take the initiative. If the advantage is large enough, the game is decided by a combination. The adversary is mated or loses a lot of material.  Anderssen's innovation lies in the high efficiency of the development. Opponents are crushed quickly.  The progress by Morphy lies in his great accuracy. Modern attacks without blunders start by him. He still loses sometimes, because he takes youthful risks. The new approach appeared for the first time in London 1851. The match tournament was organised at the occasion of the first World Fair. Sixteen players from England, Scotland, France, Germany and Hungary fought in the small St. George Club. Anderssen defeated Kieseritzky by two wins in the first round. The draw did not count. Four wins were needed in the next rounds.  The first knock-out tournament was won by a new star.  Anderssen defeated Kieseritzky by two wins in the first round. The draw did not count. Four wins were needed in the next rounds. Bird, H.: '[Exhibition Tournament, 1851.]'} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 (3. c3 d6 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bd3 g6 6. O-O Bg7 7. h3 O-O 8. d5 Nb8 9. Re1 Na6 10. Bf4 Nc7 11. Bf1 b5 12. a4 bxa4 13. Rxa4 a5 14. Bh2 Bd7 15. Ra3 a4 16.