{[%evp 23,109,33,37,4,0,4,19,13,22,0,0,0,5,-13,0,-65,0,-5,0,0,1,0,2,3,2,1,3,1,12,9,9,9,9,9,14,9,9,9,9,9,9,9,12,15,18,13,13,5,7,5,6,5,6,0,-2,-2,0,0,308,269,261,283,402,244,589,447,672,705,677,567,738,760,830,899,865,827,902,900,829,783,837,817,764,825,812,860,951,1058] D46: Semi-Slav: 5 e3 Nbd7 6 Bd3, Black avoids the Meran Golod,V: 'Inf 99/298' Myers: This game was nominated by Roald Berthelsen in Chess Mail's 1998 best game ever competition. He wrote, "Based upon thousands of CC games I have in my CC library, the following is an exciting game and one of my favourites. It has almost everything you could wish, but if it does not qualify for the best CC game ever, I suggest that Prof. Becker should qualify for the Best Annotations ever for a CC game." The following notes by Prof. Albert Becker first appeared in a special number of the Magyar Sakkvilag, over two weeks, and were translated into German and published in CAISSA in 1949. This game was contested between the players who tied for 3rd place in the event. It was played from October 10, 1912, to August 28, 1913. /// Becker: In the year 1912 there began a notably strong international CC tournament, organised by Dr. Vecsey through the chess column of the Hungarian newspaper Alkotmany. There were 10 Hungarian players, 4 from Czechoslovakia, 3 Germans, 3 Romanians and one player each from Sweden, France, Austria, and Switzerland. After a great struggle the old fox Dr Nicolas Brody from Koloszvar (Romania) emerged in first place, without losing a game. The young foxes followed him: Kosta Rozic (Zagreb) and Dr Janos Balogh (Csikszereda) and Ferenc Chalupetzky (Gyor). Game nominated by Roald Berthelsen in Chess Mail's 1998 best game ever competition:  "Based upon thousands of CC games I have in my CC library, the following is an exciting game and one of my favourites. It has almost everything you could wish, but if it does not qualify for the best CC game ever, I suggest that Prof. Becker should qualify for the Best Annotations ever for a CC game."} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 {[%cal Be7e6,Be6e5,Be5d4][%mdl 32]} (4... a6 5. c5 Bf5 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7. Be2 Qc7 8. b4 e5 9. a4 Ne4 10. Bb2 Nxc3 11. Bxc3 e4 12. Nd2 Be7 13. b5 h5 14. b6 Qb8 15. Qb3 h4 16. h3 Be6 17. Qb2 f5 18. O-O-O Nf6 19. f4 {0-1 Gaborit,J (1953)-Meredith,D (2339) 40: Monarch Assurance Open, Erin 2006 (2)}) 5. Nf3 Nbd7 $146 (5... Ne4 6. Bd3 f5 7. Ne5 Qh4 8. O-O Bd6 9. f3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Nd7 11. g3 Qh3 12. f4 Nf6 13. cxd5 exd5 14. c4 Be6 15. Rb1 h5 16. Rf2 Bxe5 17. fxe5 h4 18. exf6 hxg3 19. Rg2 dxc4 20. fxg7 {1-0 Chamberlain,A-Grimmer,B Great Britain 1995} Rh7 21. Bf1 Rxg7 22. Rxg3 Rxg3+ 23. hxg3 Qxg3+ 24. Bg2 O-O-O 25. Qf1 Rg8 26. Rb2 b5 27. d5 c3 28. Re2 cxd5 29. Rf2 Bd7 30. Qd3 Qe5 31. Kf1 Rg3 32. Qxd5 Qxd5 33. Bxd5 a5 34. e4 b4 35. exf5 {1-0 Chalupetzky,F-Balogh,J Alkotmany corr 1912} Bb5+ 36. Re2 Rd3 37. Be6+ Bd7 38. Bg5 a4 39. f6 Bxe6 40. Rxe6 Rf3+ 41. Ke2 Rf5 42. Kd3 Kd7 43. Re7+ Kd6 44. Bh4 Rf3+ 45. Kc2 Kd5 46. Re2 Rf4 47. Rf2 Rxf2+ 48. Bxf2 Ke6 49. Bd4 a3 50. Kb3 {1-0 Chalupetzky,F-Balogh,J Alkotmany tournament 1912}) (5... a6 6. b3 Nbd7 7. Bb2 Bd6 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O b5 10. Qc2 Bb7 11. e4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qxe4 bxc4 14. bxc4 Nf6 15. Qe3 Qe7 16. Rab1 Ng4 17. Qb3 c5 18. dxc5 Bxc5 19. h3 Bxf3 20. Qxf3 {½-½ Rodshtein,M (2530)-Golod,V (2597) 99/298 Dresden 2007}) 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O e5 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. e4 exd4 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 h6 13. h3 Qf6 14. Rd1 {[%cal Of3d4]} Ne5 15. Nxd4 {The position is equal.} Nxd3 16. Qxd3 Qe5 17. Nf3 {Repels Qh2+} Qh5 18. Re1 {Dodges Re8} Bf5 {[%mdl 1024] Black has compensation.} 19. Qe3 {[%eval -65,23]} ({White should play} 19. Qd1 $11 {[%eval 0,26]}) 19... Bd7 {[%eval 0,25] This pair of bishops is nice.} (19... Rae8 $15 {[%eval -65,23]} 20. Qxe8 Rxe8 21. Rxe8+ Kh7) 20. Qb3 Rfe8 21. Bd2 b6 22. Nd4 Re5 23. Rxe5 Qxe5 24. Nf3 {Dodges Qh2+} Qh5 25. Re1 Re8 26. Rxe8+ Bxe8 27. a3 Qf5 28. Bb4 Qb1+ 29. Ne1 Be5 30. Bc3 Qe4 31. Qd1 Bd6 32. Qf3 Qxf3 33. Nxf3 $11 {[%mdl 4096] Endgame. KBB-KBN} Kf8 34. Nd4 g6 {Against Nf5} 35. Kf1 Ke7 36. Ke2 Bc5 37. Kd3 Kd6 38. Kc4 a6 {[%cal Ba7a6,Ba6a5][%mdl 32]} 39. Bb4 Bxb4 40. axb4 {[%cal Ba3b4,Bb4b5][%mdl 32] Hoping for b5. KB-KN} f6 $2 {[%eval 308,29][%mdl 8192] [#] White stays focused until the end.} (40... b5+ $11 {[%eval 0,22] and Black stays safe.} 41. Kc3 Kxd5) 41. b5 $1 $18 a5 {[#]} 42. Ne2 $1 Bf7 {[%eval 402,35]} (42... g5 $142 {[%eval 283,27]} 43. Nc3 Bf7) 43. Nc3 Ke5 $2 {[%eval 589,26]} (43... g5 {[%eval 244,21]} 44. g3 h5) 44. g3 {White is clearly winning.} g5 {[%eval 672,29] [#]} (44... Kd6 $142 {[%eval 447,25]} 45. Kd4 Be8) 45. f4+ $1 {[%mdl 512]} gxf4 46. gxf4+ Kxf4 47. Na4 f5 48. Nxb6 Ke4 49. Kc5 f4 50. d6 f3 51. d7 f2 52. d8=Q {Black must now prevent Qd4+.} (52. d8=R $2 {is the wrong capture.} f1=Q (52... f1=R $2 {perishes.} 53. Na4 $18) 53. Nc8 Qf2+ (53... Qxh3 $2 54. Nd6+ Ke3 55. Nxf7 $19) 54. Kc6 Qc2+ (54... Qxb2 $2 55. Nd6+ Ke3 56. Nxf7 $19) 55. Kb6 Bd5 (55... Qxb2 $2 56. Nd6+ Kf3 57. Rf8 $19) 56. Nd6+ Kd4 $19) 52... f1=Q 53. Qd4+ Kf5 54. Nd7 {[%csl Gh3][%cal Rd4g4]} Qc1+ 55. Kd6 {Weighted Error Value: White=0.06 (flawless) /Black=0.32} 1-0


